defaultSupplementary evidence defaultfromdefault Rt Hon Alun Michael JP, defaultPolice and Crime defaultCommissioner for South WalesdefaultI am writing to provide supplementary evidence to the oral evidence I gave to the Justice 
defaultSelect Committee on the 11
defaultth
default September and I hope your colleagues will find this helpful.
defaultI very much welcome the Committee's inquiry into the co-ordination of crime reduction 
defaultpolicies. I have argued for many years now that all agencies need to take a partnership 
defaultapproach to crime reduction which is why I introduced Crime Reduction Partnerships as a 
defaultkey element in what became the 1998 Crime and Disorder Act, which I will expand on later. 
defaultIn my view one of the missing links in the system for ensuring a co-orientated approach to 
defaultcrime reduction is to ensure that the courts have a duty to pay full attention to "what works" 
defaultin reducing the likelihood 
defaultanddefault defaultthe seriousness of re-offending. At their best, the police do 
defaultserve the clear policing objective set down by Sir Robert Peel that the first duty of the police 
defaultis to prevent crime and disorder — though that cannot be done in isolation, and many of the levers in preventing crime fall outside of the hands of the police so partnership working is the 
defaultonly way forward.
defaultStrides have been made in working collaboratively with local authorities in particular, and the 
defaultNHS is another crucial partner. While there is still a long way to go, we are moving forward on that journey. I am concerned, however, that there simply hasn't been the same progress in our courts. For example, for some years I have argued that we should be much clearer 
defaultabout 
defaultour 
defaultexpectations of the Criminal Justice System as a whole. You will recall that I 
defaultmoved amendments in the House of Commons when I was a member of your committee 
defaultarguing that the Sentencing Council should be given as its key purpose the responsibility of 
defaultinforming and advising the judiciary (including magistrates) about the effectiveness of 
defaultdifferent sentences in protecting the public through reducing the likelihood of the offender 
defaultreoffending.
defaultThis view is supported by the Ministry of Justice itself which states in its written evidence to
default 
defaultyour Committee that 
default"When passing sentence, the court must have regard to the statutory
default 
defaultpurposes of sentencing, which include the reduction of crime" 
defaultand that regard must be given
default 
defaultto 
default"the cost of different sentences and their relative effectiveness in preventing re-offending... 
defaultUnderstanding what works in reoffending is 
defaulta 
defaultpriority for government.'
defaultA similar view was put forward in the Justice Select Committee's Report on Justice 
defaultReinvestment which says we should be
default:
default"looking to the judiciary to adopt an active role within local criminal justice boards so that the
defaulty
default 
defaultbetter understand the outcomes of their sentencing decisions, and are enabled to draw lessons from what happens to those they sentence; judges and magistrates should be 
defaultencouraged to work closer with criminal justice agencies as has been proved successful in community, and drug and alcohol, court initiatives
defaultand identifies that a holistic approach to reform is necessary 
default"with a very clear and explicit 
defaultstatement of the purpose of the whole system against which organisational aims can be 
defaulttested to assess their contribution to cutting the extent and seriousness of offending and 
defaultreoffending.
default”
defaultBut this message still doesn't seem to be adopted by the judiciary. Recently I asked the 
defaultchairman of the Sentencing Council, Lord Leveson, when he agreed that there was a need 
defaultto put more emphasis on informing the courts about "what works" in making offenders less 
defaultlikely to offend again, and he responded rather bizarrely by saying that we needed to ask 
defaultthat question of community sentences but not of prison sentences. Again, this is complete 
defaultcontrast to the challenge laid down by the Select Committee in 2009 that 
default"the role of the 
defaultSentencing Council 
defaultshould
default.
default be 
defaultto ensure that sentencing practice succeeds in reducing 
defaultoffending and re-offending"' 
defaultIt's encouraging that services like probation and the prisons are 
defaultkeen to work with us and very positive about the help they get from services like education, 
defaulttraining and health that come under Welsh Government.
defaultIt is important to be mindful that the context in Wales is different to that in England. In Wales 
defaultmany of the levers used in crime reduction fall within the remit of the Welsh Government 
defaultsuch as housing, health and education.
default&#xa0;
defaultAnd the Welsh Government has taken its role very seriously. Welsh Ministers have provided 
defaultus with
default 
default500 additional Community Support Officers to work with local communities to reduce 
defaultcrime; they are introducing the world's first legislation specifically targeting preventing 
defaultviolence against women; and they have provided grant funding for an innovative Community 
defaultSpeedwatch project in South Wales to target speeding in the most socio-economically 
defaultdeprived areas. They are also taking a lead role in collaborative working encouraging Local 
defaultGovernment to work on a footprint model, for example in South Wales there is a project 
defaultunderway to merge Bridgend, Swansea and Neath Port Talbot's youth services to share
default 
defaultresilience and best practice across the region.
default&#xa0;
defaultWelsh Government ha
defaults
default also sought to engage Commissioners and the four Welsh Police 
defaultand Crime Commissioners meet ministers regularly. Also, I currently sit on both the Reform 
defaultDelivery Group, and t
defaulthe Finance Sub-Group working in 
defaultpartnership with Ministers and Local 
defaultGovernment leaders to develop a response to current challenges. These are opportunities 
defaultnot afforded to my counterparts on the other side of Offa's Dyke.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, much as I applaud national commitment to crime reduction, it cannot just be done 
defaultnationally. A national strategy for crime reduction will only work as an aggregation of local 
defaultaction and with an understanding of the local context.
default&#xa0;
defaultOne of the key partnerships in reducing crime is the health service, and I take a victim-
defaultcentred approach seeing crime as a public health problem — both in terms of reducing 
defaultvictims who suffer visible injuries as a result of a violent crime, as well as the psychological impact on victims who may have suffered from the effects of long term anti-social behaviour, 
defaultfor example. I have attached an essay I wrote earlier in the year which outlines the approach 
default&#xa0;
defaultI am taking and the ways in which I am working with partners.
default 
defaultI am also working more widely with partners across South Wales to reduce crime through 
defaultSafer South Wales — a board which meets quarterly and brings together the Police with local 
defaultcouncils, Youth Offending Team managers, Probation, the Ambulance and Fire services and 
defaultHealth Board representatives. This gives us a broad range of perspectives to share 
defaultconcerns and work together on a co-ordinated approach. For more specialised issues on 
defaultcriminal justice matters, I have reconstituted the South Wales Criminal Justice Board 
defaultbringing together strategic leads from the Criminal Justice Agencies to work towards a more 
defaultefficient and effective system and increase confidence in the system in South Wales. I also 
defaultmeet the Safer South Wales Action group — a more practitioner led group which co-ordinates 
defaultthe delivery of strategy from Safer South Wales across the force area.
default&#xa0;
defaultThese issues are central to my Police and Crime (Reduction) Plan — I have included 
defaultReduction in the title of my plan, though it is not prescribed in the legislation as I believe this is what should be at the core of everything we do. Prior to becoming an MP, as you know I 
defaultwas a youth worker in some of the most deprived areas of Cardiff and worked with young 
defaultoffenders as well as chairing the (then) City Juvenile Bench. I saw the impact that youth 
defaultoffending had not only on the victims of crime, but on the future of the offenders themselves 
defaultwho became weighted down with criminal records before they even finished school. That is 
defaultwhy I established Youth Offending Teams in the 1998 Crime and Disorder Act which have 
defaultbeen hugely successful in reducing offending. The upper age limit of 18 was there simply 
defaultbecause it made sense to tackle offending at a young age rather than being a fixed ceiling. I 
defaulthave therefore made it a priority in my Plan not only to continue working on tackling youth 
defaultoffending, but to extend this to the 18-25 age group.
default&#xa0;
defaultH
defaultaving said that, it is vital that at the heart of all of my work on crime reduction are victims of 
defaultcrime — and witnesses of crime who often themselves feel victimised. When the Justice Select Committee inquired into the needs of victims, I asked the then Chief Executive of 
defaultVictim Support to summarise what victims want and need. She answered that what victims 
defaultwant, more than anything else (other than not to have become a victim in the first place) is to know that it's not going to happen again
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe need to make sure that victims are treated properly within the criminal justice system. Going to court is too, often an experience of re-victimisation, and that must change. But it is 
defaultalso imperative that we prevent offending, reoffending and re-victimisation — prevention here 
defaultis most definitely better than cure.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe police role is vital - not on their own, but as part of the team with other agencies. 
defaultVictims need to see the police as being "on their side" and I strongly support my Chief 
defaultConstable's commitment to improving victim satisfaction with the police response to crime 
defaultand anti-social behaviour.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis was my philosophy in the development of the 1998 Crime and Disorder Act, not only 
defaultintroducing local partnerships and evidence based policing in Youth Offending Teams but 
defaultextending this into wider community safety through Crime Reduction Partnerships renamed 
default"Community Safety Partnerships" in Wales - which have quietly and effectively beavered 
defaultaway at making the public safer in our communities bringing together the Police, Probation, Fire and Health services with Local Authorities at a local level. This should be a cross party 
defaultmantra because these principles were reinforced in the 2011 Police and Social 
defaultResponsibility Act and in the role of Police and Crime Commissioners.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt's worked across England and Wales, but I suggest that it has worked particularly well in 
defaultSouth Wales because it fits with the nature of strong local communities and the style of police leadership in recent times. We've also seen strong collaboration between the four 
defaultWelsh chief constables and their teams, providing a healthy precursor for the arrival of 
defaultcommissioners with the same combination of being both independent in spirit and 
defaultcollaborative in practical matters. And that's been helped by the style of Government in 
defaultWales, with the emphasis on a "public health" approach and on protecting services and 
defaultcollaborative working.
default&#xa0;
defaultAnother key success of the 1998 Act was the Anti-social Behaviour Order — more commonly 
defaultknown as the ASBO. This arose from widespread public concern with low-level antisocial behaviour and not just with serious crime. Thankfully few people are directly affected by 
defaulthomicide but large numbers of people in South Wales know about litter and graffiti and noise 
defaultnuisance and the trauma of living next to the "neighbours from hell
default.
default”
default&#xa0;
defaultAnd we also recognised the complexity of the public response to crime and disorder. During 
defaultdozens of meetings on run-down estates up and down the country I heard the authentic 
defaultvoice of local anger about local youngsters being out of control, only for the same person to 
defaultsay later in the meeting ".... and there's nothing for the kids to do around here". Many of 
defaultthose who most passionately asked us to be "tough on crime" also demanded action to 
default"tackle the causes of crime".
default&#xa0;
defaultI had never intended for the order to be used against young people who do not have a well 
defaultdeveloped sense of risk — and the high breach rate amongst young people, one of the 
defaultjustifications being used by the current Government to scrap the ASBO, supports my view 
defaultthat these types of orders just don't work for that age group. They were intended for adults and indeed the Act itself applied the ASBO only to adults.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe reason that the ASBO worked well is that whilst the Criminal Justice System is very 
defaultgood at looking a
defaultt a
default snapshot of a single event, it is not very good at dealing with the moving picture of low-level crimes which can have a real impact on quality of life, both for individuals and communities. That's why I believe there is still a key role for the ASBO in tackling crime.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt was introduced as a civil order, which meant that professional witnesses could be used in 
defaultcourt, for example Housing Officers, Community workers, and Police Officers. As intended, 
defaultthat protects victims from any negative repercussions from offenders and makes early 
defaultintervention more likely. A breach of the Order would then be considered a criminal offence 
defaultand be subject to the higher burden of proof, and the offender arrested as a deterrent.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe involvement of housing authorities and local authorities as well as the police was 
defaultanother recognition that crime reduction isn't something the police can deal with in isolation.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe figures show that most anti-social behaviour stops following a letter or some alert from 
defaultan authority that they are committing anti-social behaviour (65% after the first intervention, 86% after two and 93% by the third intervention). I think there is a good case for intervening 
defaultat the start — making people aware that they are causing a problem before neighbourhood relations deteriorate — and using community mediation to let offenders hear how their actions 
defaultare impacting on the lives of others. That's the way to enable people to escape from even 
defaultgetting an order or an injunction against them. Such an approach has benefits socially, 
defaultenvironmentally and financially, and it works.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, I also think that we need some form of deterrent. That was why I thought, and still 
defaultthink, it is vital there is the threat of arrest, a criminal prosecution and potentially even jail for 
defaultserious breaches. Our police tell me that these orders are being used to manage offenders 
defaultwithin the community, through the threat that if they do not comply they are liable to have the 
defaultpolice come knocking. Nationally, changes of direction are damaging to local work and local
default 
defaultaccountability and retard partnerships and working patterns developed over a number of 
defaultyears.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis all links back to the findings of the Justice Reinvestment report by the Justice Select 
defaultCommittee that a number of the levers which affect crime and anti-social behaviour fall 
defaultoutside of the criminal justice system'. A co-ordinated partnership approach is the only way 
defaultto ensure effective crime prevention, and I very much welcome the inquiry by the Select Committee in this area because it is an approach that works.
default&#xa0;
defaultI welcome the Ministry's commitment to providing up to 12 months support for all offenders —
defaultincluding those who have served less than 12 months. But this work needs resources and 
defaultstability and efforts need to be made to ensure this is a truly joined up approach. Drug and 
defaultalcohol intervention, mental health issues, housing services, education and training, 
defaultcounselling and relationship services are all important if the cycle of offending is to be 
defaultbroken. As a local prison governor said to me, it's about making sure on release someone 
defaultturns left to local services, instead of right to the nearest pub.
default&#xa0;
defaultI have heard too many times from prisoners and ex-prisoners that they are better off inside with routine, hot meals and a bed than on the outside. It's shocking that only one third of 
defaultprisoners reported being in paid employment in the 4 weeks before custody, that 13% 
defaultreported never having had a job, 15% were homeless before custody and 25% were 
defaultsuffering from anxiety and depression
defaultv
default.
default 
defaultThat simply isn't right.
default&#xa0;
defaultAgainst this background the forthcoming changes to the Probation Service as well as the 
defaultshift in legislation to tackle anti-social behaviour are deeply worrying. These changes 
defaultthreaten to tear up partnerships and creating a great deal of uncertainty in the sector fuelled 
defaultby a lack of evidence from pilots — which were cancelled in Wales. Mr Richard Johnson told 
defaultthe Committee on 2 July 2013 that if you want the system to work, you would attach funding 
defaultdirectly to an individual that would otherwise go to probation, prisons, police, health, 
defaultemployment and housing to ensure a co-ordinated approach. The worst possible outcome 
defaultwould be a silo mentality with each service only interested in their bit of the puzzle. Ironically 
defaultthere is a better level of collaboration now than for many -years. We can only hope that will survive the current round of changes.
default&#xa0;
defaultAnd Justice cannot be totally divorced from Social Justice. Police and Local Government 
defaultface hugely reduced budgets as are partner agencies and third sector organisations and 
defaultmeanwhile welfare reforms are reducing the support available to people in our poorest 
defaultcommunities. Pushing people to such dire situations can only result in an increase in 
defaultadditional pressure on services later on. It makes early intervention even more difficult at the 
defaultvery time when we need to create head room for services. Prisons and police cells should 
defaultnot be used as a backstop where other agencies have failed.
default&#xa0;
defaultI 
defaultam pleased to say that unlike some past periods of financial crisis, when there was a 
defaulttendency to withdraw into "core services", many public bodies fully appreciate that only joint 
defaultworking can bring about more effective preventative work and improved standards of 
defaultdelivery. Strategic demands from government, the service demands of the end user, and 
defaulteffectiveness in serving the public all require a more joined-up approach in order to enable each part of the public sector to do more with less while coping with the effects of fundin
defaultg 
defaultcuts.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis approach is actually supported in 
defaultrelation to community safety by 
defaultboth the 1998 Crime 
defaultand Disorder Act, and the 2011 P
defaultolice and Social Responsibility 
defaultAct.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe 1998 Act states:
default&#xa0;
default"Section 17: Duty to consider crime and disorder implications.
default(1)Without prejudice to any other obligation imposed on it, it shall be the duty 
defaultof each authority to which this section applies to exercise its various functions 
defaultwith 
defaultdue regard to the likely effect of the exercise of those functions on, defaultand the need to do all that it reasonably can to prevent, crime and defaultdisorder in its area."defaultThe 2011 Act reaffirms this, and includes a specific reference to the Police and Crime 
defaultCommissioner's responsibilities with regards to partnership working and engagement with 
defaultthe Criminal Justice System:
default1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Police &amp; Crime Commissioner must, in exercising his functions, have regard to 
defaultthe relevant priorities of each responsible authority.
default2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
