defaultPPC 14 — Written Evidence from the Ministry of Justice, Paragraphs 38
default&#xa0;defaultReducing harmdefault: Using a public health approach to tackling crimedefaultIt's a great irony that one of the two great clarion calls for common sense on combatting crime came from 
defaulta Conservative Leader while the other came from a Labour Leader — over 150 years apart.
defaultEach offered powerful slogans based in clear principles and borne out by evidence. They show that 
defaultneither political theory nor populist rhetoric can adequately define the role of the police in meeting the 
defaultprime responsibility of the State - to protect its citizens.
defaultMy first champion for common sense is Sir Robert Peel, whose nine "Peelian 
defaultPrinciples" (distilled by later
default 
defaultcommentators from his speeches) boil down to two key principles :
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default"The basic mission for the police is to prevent crime and disorder."
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default"The Police are the public and the public are the police."
defaultMy second champion is Tony Blair whose approach was famously summed up in a single message
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default"We must be Tough on Crime and Tough on the Causes of Crime."
defaultActually, it nearly didn't become famous. Tony became tired of repeating the message, and as his deputy I 
defaulthad to keep reinstating it in one speech after another until a sarcastic comment by Michael Howard (Home 
defaultSecretary at the time) provided the oxygen of media attention and we were able to expound and develop the practical ideas that underpinned the slogan.
defaultWe identified widespread public concern with low-level antisocial behaviour and not just with serious 
defaultcrime. Thankfully few people are directly affected by homicide but large numbers of people in South 
defaultWales know about litter and graffiti and noise nuisance and the trauma of living next to the "neighbours from hell".
defaultAnd we also recognised the complexity of the public response to crime and disorder. During dozens of meetings on run-down estates up and down the country I heard the authentic voice of local anger about 
defaultlocal youngsters being out of control, only for the same person to say later in the meeting ".... and there's 
defaultnothing for the kids to do around here". Many of those who most passionately asked us to be "tough on 
defaultcrime" also demanded action to "tackle the causes of crime". Our "slogan" grew out of listening to local 
defaultexperience.
defaultThe imperative for sophisticated and responsible police leadership became clear after the polarised period of the Miners' Strike, when many Chief Constables sought to re-connect the polic
defaulte with the
default community. 
defaultThey also gave enthusiastic support to the principles of partnership set out in the Crime and Disorder Act 
default1998. Crime and Disorder Partnerships, Youth Offending Teams, the Youth Justice Board and preventative 
defaultinterventions like the Anti-social Behaviour Order have all helped to make a real and lasting impact on 
defaultcrime levels across England and Wales. As Peel rightly said, 
default"the efficiency and effectiveness of the police defaultis proved through the absence of crime and not through the evidence of police action in dealing with defaultcrime".defaultThe most significant statement of evidence-based principles came in December 2009 with a unanimous 
defaultcross-party report from the Justice Select Committee after a major investigation into 
defaultJustice Reinvestment. default"If you had all the money that goes into the Criminal Justice System today, would you spend it in the same 
defaultway
default?" Simp
defaultle answer
default: "No!"
