defaultIt showed that most of the public policy factors that affect levels of crime and disorder are outside the 
defaulthands of the police and the Criminal Justice System. Education, skills training, jobs, opportunity, housing, 
defaultsubstance misuse, alcohol abuse, mental health and early intervention to "nip things in the bud" 
defaultDOdefault defaultaffect 
defaultcrime levels.
defaultIn particular, mental health is an issue that is raised regularly. Research has shown that 70% of the prison 
defaultpopulation has two or more mental health disorders. So we are failing to identify people with mental 
defaulthealth conditions and failing to get them to the help they need. Individuals with mental health needs 
defaultoften end up in police custody instead of getting the help they need. In contrast the NHS is expected to 
defaulthelp those with other on-going (or even "untreatable") conditions, like diabetes or a heart condition. A 
defaultcrisis for them may result in fast transit to A&amp;E, but not a trip to police cells and that's what needs to 
defaultchange.
defaultSo, if most of the levers are outside the hands of the police, how can a Police &amp; Crime Commissioner make 
defaulta real impact
default?
