defaultA partnership approach to prevention
defaultHere's what they mean in practice:
defaultA defaultvictim-based approachdefaultWhen the Justice Select Committee enquired into the needs of victims, I asked the then Chief Executive of 
defaultVictim Support to summarise what victims want and need. She answered that what victims want, more 
defaultthan anything else (other than not to have become a victim in the first place) is to know that it's not going 
defaultto happen again.
defaultWe need to make sure that victims are treated properly within the criminal justice system. Going to court 
defaultis too often an experience of re-victimisation, and that must change. But it is also imperative that we 
defaultprevent offending, re-offending and re-victimisation .
defaultThe police role is vital - not on their own, but as part of the team with other agencies. Victims need to see 
defaultthe police as being "on their side" and I strongly support my Chief Constable's commitment to improving 
defaultthe satisfaction of victims with the police response to crime and anti-social behaviour.
defaultRestorative justice too must be victim-centred, enabling the victim's voice to be heard while challenging 
defaultthe offender and tackling the "relational deficit" which is exhibited by so many offenders.
defaultEvidence-based approachdefaultPreparing evidence for the court is central to police professionalism, so it may seem redundant to demand an evidence-based approach to policing. But an evidence-based approach to crime reduction i
defaults different,
default and for a time was not seen as central to the police as a "blue light" service. The "blue light service" of 
defaultreactive policing is essential to the public and central to the role of the police - but it's 
defaultreactive defaultrather than 
defaultpreventative.default&#xa0;
defaultThe "can do" attitude of the police to tackling problems is a great strength. When a problem arises, their 
defaultinstinctive response is "let me take that away and sort it". —However this can be a weakness if the levers of 
defaultpreventative action lie with other people. So the big challenge for a Commissioner is to endorse the 
defaultaction-orientated approach while leading the search for "what works" and taking a clinical approach to 
defaultasking "why does this bad stuff happen?" and bringing about change.
defaultMy passionate belief in the partnership approach comes from a history of working across different 
defaultagencies long before I entered Parliament. I worked with young offenders, I sought to reduce offending 
defaultlocally, I worked in an analytic interagency context as a youth worker and I chaired the city's Juvenile 
defaultBench (as it then was). An "action research" project in the Ely area of Cardiff with a young researcher —
defaultnow Prof Howard Williamson of the University of South Wales made a massive impact on me. Intensive 
defaultwork proved that people in different professions "knew" the area in general, but totally misunderstood the 
defaultdetail at the granular local level. It also proved that a silo approach by agencies and professions is not just 
defaultineffective but totally counter-productive.
defaultEarlier, being involved in a major project on "Working Together for Children and their Families", led by the 
defaultlate great Barbara Kahan, opened my eyes to the ineffectiveness of a great deal of public policy.
defaultWe now have ample proof that an evidence-based approach to partnership works. The Crime and Disorder 
defaultReduction Partnerships required by the 1998 Act (Community Safety Partnerships in Wales) are a clear 
defaultsuccess, although the methodology of audit, evidence collection and analysis has not been as methodical 
defaultas I intended.
defaultThe effectiveness of a rigorous approach is shown by the Cardiff Violence Reduction Programme led by 
defaultProf Jonathan Shepherd of Cardiff University's Medical School. Jonathan approached me in the mid-90s to 
defaultargue that a scientific approach could cut violence significantly. His in-tray for treatment of facial injuries 
defaultfrom car accidents was going down (in number and seriousness) but his in-tray of victims of violence was escalating.
defaultIt's a long story, but analysing incidents which brought victims of violence to A&amp;E led to significant and 
defaultsustained reductions in the number and seriousness of violent incidents. Peer-reviewed published 
defaultevidence puts this beyond doubt. A crucial aspect of my Police and Crime Plan, supported by the Welsh 
defaultHealth Minister, Mark Drakeford AM, is to take a similar baseline approach to all Accident and Emergency 
defaultDepartments across South Wales.
defaultCommitment to partnership and preventative approaches defaultSo an analytic approach is vital and partnership works - provided partnership is much more than different 
defaultprofessionals just feeling comfortable with each other. I am convinced that other aspects of crime will 
defaultrespond to a similar clinical and rigorous approach. That's why partnership needs to permeate all agencies 
defaultand translate into activity on the ground — as happens in the late night triage in Cardiff where health, 
defaultpolice, local authority and Third Sector staff work amazingly well together.
defaultThe benefits are obvious and borne out in the statistics: If police have fewer crimes to deal with, they can 
defaultfocus their limited resources on improving interventions, increasing the sanction-detection levels, 
defaultimproving victim satisfaction and improving engagement with the wider public. That's consistent with Sir Robert Peel's messages. It's good for a surgeon to have fewer cases in his in-tray, for courts to deal with 
defaultfewer cases and subsequently for police officers to be s
defaultpared wasteful hours in court ……. 
defaultand it's good
default for those who do not become victims.
default&#xa0;
defaultI can only speak for South Wales, where the police have pursued this approach for several years and we 
defaulthave the enthusiastic engagement of local councils and others. The 2010 Comprehensive Spending 
defaultReview's severe cuts, compounded now by further cuts, puts this success at risk. Above all, we need to 
defaultavoid what I saw in previous recessions when many agencies retreated into their silo, narrowed their focus 
defaultand reduced interagency cooperation. Certainly in Wales there is good evidence that things are different 
defaultthis time : Welsh Government, local councils and others understand that in tough times you need more 
defaultjoint working, not less.
defaultThat's where the Police and Crime Commissioner can add value.
defaultIf many crime reduction levers are outside the hands of the police, are the police less important as a Force 
defaultand as a Profession? Certainly not
default: The role of police officers is enormously complex, coping with an 
defaultamazing range of demands from local antisocial behaviour to terrorism and extremism, from traffic to the 
defaultnight time economy, from helping vulnerable elderly people to tackling thugs and crooks, and much, much 
defaultmore. Clear operational direction by the chief constable is vital, complemented by the role of the
default 
defaultindividual police officer - a citizen to whom we have given powers to act on behalf of the rest of us.
defaultMinisterial statements and Media headlines about Police and Crime Commissioners talked of "powers" and 
default"holding chief constables to account". That's important, but any interested observer should study the "Commissioners Oath of Office". An MP's oath refers vaguely to serving the Queen as some sort of proxy 
defaultfor public service, whereas the Commissioner's Oath is detailed, complex and specific. It reflects the 
defaultcomplex role of a Commissioner, which in turn reflects the complex role of the police and I have promised 
defaultspecifically to serve the people and communities of South Wales.
defaultThe formal duties of a Commissioner are important, but it's the "and Crime" part of the role that allows an imaginative and enthusiastic Commissioner to make a real impact as a real partner for the Chief Constable, 
defaultmutually challenging but with clear areas of responsibility. The Commissioner can make the connections 
defaultacross public bodies in general and carry out the explicit duty to provide an "efficient and effective criminal 
defaultjustice system" in the local police area. Our leadership is about driving down crime 
defaultand defaultsupporting 
defaultexcellence in policing.
defaultThe way forward is clear — it's through a "public health" approach to policing. The Media portray well the 
defaultexcitement of "blue light" activities in the NHS and in the police, but it's the hidden, painstaking, evidence-based approach to making things better that matter for victims and patients. To put it another way, fewer 
defaultvictims and fewer patient spells success.
defaultThere's just one problem.
defaultFor years I believed that cutting crime would lead to people feeling safer, but that's not how it works. 
defaultWhen I ask public meetings whether the centre of Cardiff is safer or less safe than it was ten years ago, 
defaultmost people say "worse". In fact it's far safer — shown by the reduced number and seriousness of injuries 
defaultthat take victims of violence to A&amp;E.
defaultSo I want to add a "
defaultTenth Principle" to Peel's nine
default:
default&#xa0;
default"We must understand the real levels of crime, not just what is reported, and share this knowledge with the public to reduce the fear of crime".default&#xa0;
defaultAs newspapers struggle to survive, as aspects of social media become shrill and intolerant, and as the 
defaultcacophony of public opinion becomes ever more deafening, it sometimes seems hopeless to argue for 
defaulttrusting the public with the facts. Local residents are a part of the solution, rather than part of the problem. 
defaultChurchill described democracy as the worst form of government, except for all the others that have been 
defaulttried. That applies equally to the public health approach to cutting crime and disorder.
defaultIt won't make headlines, but having been given leadership responsibility by the electorate, that's the direction in which the Police and Crime Commissioner should lead the police and the public.defaultRt Hon Alun Michaeldefault7defaultthdefault September 2013default&#xa0;
